Office of Supt.
Corsicana Tex. May 1st 1883.

My dear Professor:
Your letter with
Solution of Prob. recd. Thanks –
I may have neglected to state to
you that the Prob. appeared in an
Examination which I prepared for
teachers in our Pub. Schools.
A question was sprung – as to the
correctness of Solution given by teachers,
by a member of the Board of Examiners,
(a University Regent). Lawyers deny
every thing you know. For his
benefit I asked to trouble you with it.
There can be no question as to
the correctness of your Solution
by methods of the Arithmetic.

I feel that it is not improbable
that Mr. Cole may be tendered
the place made vacant by resignation
of Col. James. In that event, the
Chair of English will be to fill.
I am no place-hunter - nor will
my manhood allow me to ask
for any place in A & M. C. yet
I am free to state to you that
I would accept the English Chair
in your College; for reasons that
are patent to you - In this
matter, I can but repeat the
phrase of the politicians "I
am in the hands of my friends"
You can mention this matter to Dr.
Smythe & Capt. Fowlks. My ambition
would prompt me to aspire
to the presidency of A & M. C.
but for the Ag. Dept. I can't see the
end of that curve.

into the News - but did not fail

not had time to work the matter
up. I learn that our School
authorities here have made
application for a Summer Normal
at this point again this Summer
+ without my knowledge have
made application for my appointment
Any points which you may
feel at liberty to give relative
to the outlook at the A & M. C.
will be appreciated. Who preaches
your sermon this year - also your
Lit. address? I go to Galveston 26th
June. I want to run over to Waco on
10th inst to see Dr. Mell Chan. Uni. Georgia
Write me soon -
Your friend J. T. Hand
